e of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:People from Northampton]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Slowthai\n| image            = Slowthai 2019 Glastonbury Festival 04.jpg\n| caption          = Slowthai at [[Glastonbury Festival]] in 2019\n| birth_name       = Tyron Kaymone Frampton\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1994|12|18}}<ref name=\"bday\">{{cite tweet|user=slowthai|number=1075051056575537154|date=2018-12-18|title= on this day 25 years ago I came to fuck the game up... also on the same day \u2018here comes the hot stepper\u2019 was number 1 and here i am on the cover of clash \ud83c\udf82 have a good day}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Northampton]], England\n| background       = solo_singer\n| instrument       = [[Rapping|Vocals]]\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| website          = {{URL|https://slowthai.com/}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[grime (music genre)|grime]]\n*{{nowrap|[[political hip hop]]}}}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[True Panther Sounds]]\n*Method Records}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]]\n*[[Mura Masa]]\n*[[Flume (musician)|Flume]]\n*[[Blue Daisy (musician)|Kwesi Darko]]\n*[[Tyler, the Creator]]\n*[[Brockhampton (band)|Brockhampton]]\n*[[Denzel Curry]]\n*[[Skepta]]\n*[[Gorillaz]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Tyron Kaymone Frampton ''' (born 18 December 1994),<ref name=\"bday\"/> better known by his stage name '''Slowthai''' (stylised in [[lowercase]]), is an English rapper. Raised in [[Northampton]],<ref name=\"background\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46705455|title=Sound of 2019: slowthai 'telling the story of the people for the people'|date=8 January 2019|publisher=[[BBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109011858/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46705455|archive-date=9 January 2019|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref> He rose to popularity in 2019 for his gritty and rough instrumentals and raw, politically charged lyrics, especially around [[Brexit]] and [[Theresa May]]\u2019s tenure as British Prime Minister.\nSlowthai placed 4th in the [[Sound of...|BBC Sound Of 2019]] and followed up in the same year with his debut studio album, ''[[Nothing Great About Britain]].'' The album was nominated for the [[Mercury Prize]]; at Slowthai\u2019s 2019 Mercury Prize ceremony performance, he held a fake severed head of British Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] on stage, generating much controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/rapper-slowthai-holds-up-fake-boris-johnson-head-on-stage-at-mercury-prize-ceremony-11814567|title=Rapper slowthai holds up fake Boris Johnson head on stage at Mercury Prize ceremony|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206151253/https://news.sky.com/story/rapper-slowthai-holds-up-fake-boris-johnson-head-on-stage-at-mercury-prize-ceremony-11814567|archive-date=2019-12-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n{{Section refimprove|date=February 2019}}\nSlowthai was born on 18 December 1994 in [[Northampton]] to a teenage mother of mixed [[Barbados|Bajan]] and [[Ireland|Irish]] descent, he was raised by his single mother in a council estate with his sister in the Lings area of Northampton. His step-father later moved in and his younger brother Michael was born with [[muscular dystrophy]] (MD). He died in 2001, aged one, which greatly affected Frampton and the family. Frampton attended [[Northampton Academy]] and in 2011 went on to attend [[Northampton College]], where he studied a Level 3 [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTEC]] in Music Technology.\n\nSlowthai frequently [[truancy|skipped school]] during his years at Northampton Academy, often spending time at a nearby underground \u201crecording studio\u201d at his friend's house, only stopping when his mother was forced to attend a compulsory court hearing. After college, Slowthai had multiple miscellaneous short stints in employment - he worked as a [[labourer]] and at a clothes shop before being sacked for breach of contract after he gave his friends employee benefits. After his dismissal, he focused entirely on music, downloading a copy of [[FL Studio]] and releasing numerous singles and an extended play under Bone Soda.\n\n== Music career ==\nThe name Slowthai originates from his childhood nickname; slow ty due to his slow speech and drawled tone.{{citation needed}} In 2016, he released his first single titled Jiggle and went on to release a string of singles via SoundCloud that were later removed.{{citation needed}}\n\nIn 2017, Slowthai partnered up with indie record label Bone Soda to release his I WISH I KNEW EP, Murder and T N Biscuits.{{citation needed}} Later in the same year, Slowthai signed his recording contract with Method Records and since has released his RUNT EP and debut studio album, ''[[Nothing Great About Britain]]'' which charted at number 9 on the [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] on the week of release<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/nothing-great-about-britain/|title=nothing great about britain &#124; full Official Chart History &#124; Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com}}</ref>.\n\nIn addition to being included in the [[BBC]]'s [[Sound of...|Sound of 2019]] poll<ref name=\"soundof2019\" /> and ''[[NME]]'''s NME 100 list,<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/the-nme-100-essential-new-artists-for-2019-2426835|title=The NME 100: Essential new artists for 2019|last=Smith|first=Thomas|date=2019-01-08|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401175930/https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/the-nme-100-essential-new-artists-for-2019-2426835|archive-date=2019-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> Slowthai has also received acclaim from publications such as ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'', [[Vevo]] and ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]''<ref name=\"diy\" /><ref name=\"vevo\" /><ref name=\"metro\" /> as well as having his debut album nominated for a [[Mercury Prize|Mercury Music Prize]].\n\nSlowthai contributed additional vocals on the song \"What's Good\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/here-are-the-full-credits-for-tyler-the-creators-new-album-igor-kanye-solange-pharrell-more/|title=Here Are the Full Credits for Tyler, the Creator\u2019s New Album IGOR: Kanye, Solange, Pharrell, More|website=Pitchfork}}</ref> from [[Tyler, the Creator|Tyler, The Creator's]] album ''[[Igor (album)|Igor]]''. He also featured on \"Heaven Belongs To You\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/slowthai-guest-brockhampton-new-song-heaven-belongs-to-you-ginger-album-2540957|title=Hear Slowthai appear on Brockhampton\u2019s new song, \u2018Heaven Belongs To You\u2019|date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> from [[Brockhampton (band)|Brockhampton]]'s album ''[[Ginger (Brockhampton album)|Ginger]]'' and later joined their HBTY North American tour in 2019 as the special guest<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/brockhampton-announce-tour-with-slowthai/|title=BROCKHAMPTON Announce Tour With slowthai|website=Pitchfork}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2020, Slowthai was featured alongside UK punk band [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]] on [[Gorillaz]]'s single \"[[Momentary Bliss]]\". The single was the first \"episode\" of their ''Song Machine'' project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gorillaz-new-music-video-series-song-machine-details-944519/|title=Gorillaz Detail New Music, Video Series 'Song Machine'|last=Blistein|first=Jon|last2=Blistein|first2=Jon|date=2020-01-29|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, after winning the Hero of the Year award at the [[NME Awards]], Slowthai dropped his microphone into the crowd, which was then thrown back at him along with a drink. Slowthai then threw his own drink and jumped into the crowd. Although viewers complained of his comments to Canadian comedia [[Katherine Ryan]], Ryan said Slowthai \"didn't make me uncomfortable\". He has since apologised to Ryan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-51485561|title=NME Awards: Slowthai apologises to Katherine Ryan after 'shameful actions'|access-date=Feb 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nHis music has been categorised as [[grime (music genre)|grime]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gorman |first1=Michael |title=Slowthai is Exactly What Grime Needed |url=https://thesidelineobserver.com/2019/06/11/slowthai-is-exactly-what-grime-needed/ |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> and [[hip hop music|hip hop]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Norris |first1=John |title=Tyron Frampton Comes Alive: U.K. Rapper Slowthai Brings His Bars to America |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8517936/slowthai-interview-nothing-great-about-britain |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> He often includes elements of [[punk rock]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Christie |first1=Caroline |title=slowthai revives the raw energy of punk for today\u2019s fractured Britain |website=[[Document Journal]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |title=Slowthai: Nothing Great About Britain review \u2013 snarling in the face of power |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/may/16/slowthai-nothing-great-about-britain-album-review |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> leading to the categorisation of grime-punk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Empire |first1=Kitty |title=Slowthai review \u2013 grandmaster of mayhem |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/oct/19/slowthai-swg3-glasgow-review |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ross |first1=Alex Robert |title=Slowthai\u2019s jacked union |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/05/17/slowthai-nothing-great-about-britain-interview |website=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> In a 2019 article for the [[BBC]], Kev Geoghegan described him as \"either a grime MC making punk music or a punk making rap music\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geoghegan |first1=Kev |title=Sound of 2019: slowthai 'telling the story of the people for the people' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46705455 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> In an article for [[Vice Media]], Niloufar Haidari described his music as \"caustically witty bars over abrasive beats that blend grime, [[trap music|trap]], [[Soundcloud rap]] and even punk and [[screamo]]\".<ref name=\"Vice\" />\n\nHe has cited musical influences including [[Gesaffelstein]], [[Juelz Santana]], [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]], [[Radiohead]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Mount Kimbie]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Justice (band)|Justice]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and [[Die Antwoord]].<ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite web |last1=Haidari |first1=Niloufar |title=slowthai's Music is Halfway Between Rap and Punk and So Are His Influences |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3m7qb/slowthais-youtube-music-unearthed-interview-2018 |website=[[Vice Media]] |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/55439/slowthai/|title=Slowthai {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=25 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601102116/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/55439/slowthai/|archive-date=1 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Albums|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=24 May 2019|format=To access, go to \"2019\" > \"24-May-19\" and filter by \"Slowthai\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016170242/http://www.irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Albums|archive-date=16 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nothing Great About Britain]]''\n| \n* Release: 17 May 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2019/02/20/slowthai-debut-album-nothing-great-about-britain-peace-of-mind-video-watch|title=Slowthai announces debut album 'Nothing Great About Britain' with 'Peace of Mind' video|publisher=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=20 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329074516/http://diymag.com/2019/02/20/slowthai-debut-album-nothing-great-about-britain-peace-of-mind-video-watch|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Label: Method\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| 9 || 64\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''I WISH I KNEW \u30ce\u30ce''\n| \n* Release: 3 November 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/i-wish-i-knew-%E3%83%8E%E3%83%8E-ep/1300728390|title=I WISH I KNEW \u30ce\u30ce - EP by slowthai|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (UK)|date=3 November 2017|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n* Label: Bone Soda\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''RUNT''\n| \n* Release: 14 September 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/runt-ep/1435601550