.<ref>[https://www.abebooks.com/book-search/author/behrbohm-hermann/ \u00dcber die Algebraizit\u00e4t der Meromorphismen eines elliptischen Funktionenk\u00f6rpers Nachrichten von der Gesellschaft der Wissenschaften zu G\u00f6ttingen, Reihe:Mathematisch-Physikalische Klasse - Fachgruppe 1 Mathematik Neue Folge Band 1 - Nr.8, Behrbohm Hermann: Published by Berlin, Weidmann Verlag, 1935]</ref> In 1944 he was promoted [[doctor]] in [[mathematics]] and [[physics]].\n\nBehrbohm also had great difficulties in getting married to his first wife because of the regulations in Nazi Germany. She had difficulties obtaining biological purity certificates (unknown father) and thus being able to marry him, which was possible only in 1940.\n\n=== Messerschmitt===\nHe was recruited in 1937 to [[Messerschmitt]]\u2019s [[Aerodynamics]] department in [[Augsburg]]. He was also involved in a part-time  assignment from 1944 at the Ministry of Aviation in [[Vienna]].\n\n=== French occupation ===\nAs a Messerschmitt employee, he [[1945]] was initially a [[prisoner of war]] but [[1946]] was recruited by BEE (French Aerodynamic Research and Development Institute) with operations in [[Emmendingen]] and [[Weil am Rhein]] in [[French occupation zone in Germany]].\n\nAfter the formation of the [[Federal Republic of Germany]] [[1949]] and the cessation of occupation, the opportunities were greater to find scientifically interesting work abroad and Behrbohm received offers from France and other countries.\n\n=== Saab===\nHermann chose [[1951]] to start working on [[Saab AB | Saab]] moving to [[Link\u00f6ping]] with his family who became naturalized Swedes.\nThe motives for choosing to work for Saab were the projects [[Saab 32 Lansen]] and [[Saab 35 Draken]] under [[Erik Bratt]] and [[Tore Gullstrand]].<ref> \"[https://www.e-pic.se/Aircraft/Aircraft-sorted-by-type/SAAB/SAAB-32-Lansen/i-bpQqNfS Note that Herman Behbohm was a French prisoner of war in 1945 and came not (as claimed) with [[Frid W\u00e4nstr\u00f6m]] and the Messerschmitt drawings that Saab acquired in Switzerland in 1945 that laid the foundation for [[Saab 29 Tunnan]], ref Margareta Behrbohm] \"</ref> Being a specialist in aerodynamics is a narrow labor market with few employers in the world who have sufficient resources to create good results. Saab where they built up operations and Sweden's ambitions gave Hermann the opportunities.\n\nHermann remained at Saab until his retirement in 1972. During the years 1960-64 he was head of the [[Aerodynamics]] department, also participated in the projects [[Saab 37 Viggen]] and [[Saab 105]] and published a large number of articles in aerodynamics.<ref>\"[http://runeberg.org/tektid/1952/1078.html Teknisk Tidskrift / \u00c5rg\u00e5ng 82. 1952 / 1062]\"</ref> He was esteemed and won the Swedish Aeronautical Society\u2019s Thulin Medal [[1968]] in silver.\n\nHermann Behrbohm and [[Bertil Dillner]] made significant efforts in the design of [[Saab 37 Viggen]], and in particular the design and tests of the nose wing construction.<ref>\"[http://libris.kb.se/bib/11717818 Flyghistorisk revy, 0345-3413, System 37 Viggen, Artikel av Erik Bratt]\"</ref>\n\nAfter retirement, he moved with his second wife to her home town in the south [[England]] and lived there afterwards.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of aviators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Behrbohm, Hermann}}\n[[Category: Men]]\n[[Category: People from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Aircraft designers]]\n[[Category:20th-century men]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Behrbohm"}
{"title_page": "The House on Parchment Street", "text_new": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The House on Parchment Street\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = The House on Parchment Street.jpg\n| caption = Cover of first edition\n| author        = [[Patricia A. McKillip]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Charles Robinson\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Atheneum Books|Atheneum]]\n| release_date  = 1973\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print ([[hardcover]])\n| pages         = 190\n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''The House on Parchment Street''''' is a [[fantasy]] [[ghost story]] [[novel]] for juvenile readers by [[Patricia A. McKillip]], first published in hardcover by [[Atheneum Books|Atheneum]] in 1973 and reprinted in trade paperback by the same publisher in March 1978 and April 1991.<ref name=\"ISFDB\">{{isfdb title|id=1307}}</ref> It bears the distinction, along with ''[[The Throme of the Erril of Sherill]]'' (also 1973), of being one of McKillip's first published books.<ref name=\"ISFDB\"/>\n\n==Summary==\nCarol, a self-reliant teen-aged American girl, is sent to [[England]] to stay a month with relatives currently living in a big old rented house on Parchment Street, next to a graveyard in a small village. Her first encounter with the locals involves a group of delinquent bullies, whom she drives away, only to learn they're the cronies of her cousin Bruce. Naturally, she and Bruce don't immediately hit it off well with each other.\n\nAfter various misadventures she witnesses a signal event in the cellar\u2014the [[ghost]] of a swordsman dressed in black, who disappears into a wall. After she learns Bruce has also seen the ghost, the two enter a tentative alliance to investigate the mystery. The first ghost and another, this one of a young girl, are trapped in a daily reenactment of traumatic events that originally took place during the [[English Civil War]], over three hundred years before. Only the children seem able to perceive the ghosts; neither Carol's hidebound Uncle Harold nor the more open-minded Father Malory can see them.\n\nEventually Carol and Bruce uncover a walled-up tunnel leading from the cellar of the house to the nearby church, following the ghosts to the bloody conclusion of their reenactments, and are able to lay them to rest by burying their bones, which they discover in the tunnel. In the course of their adventure they develop a more sympathetic relationship.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' calls the book a \"satisfying adventure ... just what young readers would order if they had the imagination to dream it up themselves,\" and goes on to say that \"[t]hough the story lacks the intriguing psychological ambiguity of, say, [[Zilpha Keatley Snyder|Zilpha Snyder]]'s ghost stories, McKillip blends history, supernatural occurrences, and firm contemporary reality with a sure sense of drama and detail that brings all three worlds to simultaneous life.\"<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/patricia-mckillip/the-house-on-parchment-street/ Review] in ''Kirkus Reviews'', Mar. 21, 1973.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Patricia A. McKillip}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:House on Parchment Street, The}}\n[[Category:Novels by Patricia A. McKillip]]\n[[Category:1973 American novels]]\n[[Category:1973 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The House on Parchment Street\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = The House on Parchment Street.jpg\n| caption = Cover of first edition\n| author        = [[Patricia A. McKillip]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Charles Robinson\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Atheneum Books|Atheneum]]\n| release_date  = 1973\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print ([[hardcover]])\n| pages         = 190\n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = [[The Throme of the Erril of Sherill]]\n}}\n'''''The House on Parchment Street''''' is a [[fantasy]] [[ghost story]] [[novel]] for juvenile readers by [[Patricia A. McKillip]], first published in hardcover by [[Atheneum Books|Atheneum]] in 1973 and reprinted in trade paperback by the same publisher in March 1978 and April 1991.<ref name=\"ISFDB\">{{isfdb title|id=1307}}</ref> It bears the distinction, along with ''[[The Throme of the Erril of Sherill]]'' (also 1973), of being one of McKillip's first published books.<ref name=\"ISFDB\"/>\n\n==Summary==\nCarol, a self-reliant teen-aged American girl, is sent to [[England]] to stay a month with relatives currently living in a big old rented house on Parchment Street, next to a graveyard in a small village. Her first encounter with the locals involves a group of delinquent bullies, whom she drives away, only to learn they're the cronies of her cousin Bruce. Naturally, she and Bruce don't immediately hit it off well with each other.\n\nAfter various misadventures she witnesses a signal event in the cellar\u2014the [[ghost]] of a swordsman dressed in black, who disappears into a wall. After she learns Bruce has also seen the ghost, the two enter a tentative alliance to investigate the mystery. The first ghost and another, this one of a young girl, are trapped in a daily reenactment of traumatic events that originally took place during the [[English Civil War]], over three hundred years before. Only the children seem able to perceive the ghosts; neither Carol's hidebound Uncle Harold nor the more open-minded Father Malory can see them.\n\nEventually Carol and Bruce uncover a walled-up tunnel leading from the cellar of the house to the nearby church, following the ghosts to the bloody conclusion of their reenactments, and are able to lay them to rest by burying their bones, which they discover in the tunnel. In the course of their adventure they develop a more sympathetic relationship.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' calls the book a \"satisfying adventure ... just what young readers would order if they had the imagination to dream it up themselves,\" and goes on to say that \"[t]hough the story lacks the intriguing psychological ambiguity of, say, [[Zilpha Keatley Snyder|Zilpha Snyder]]'s ghost stories, McKillip blends history, supernatural occurrences, and firm contemporary reality with a sure sense of drama and detail that brings all three worlds to simultaneous life.\"<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/patricia-mckillip/the-house-on-parchment-street/ Review] in ''Kirkus Reviews'', Mar. 21, 1973.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Patricia A. McKillip}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:House on Parchment Street, The}}\n[[Category:Novels by Patricia A. McKillip]]\n[[Category:1973 American novels]]\n[[Category:1973 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n", "name_user": "Veritycheck", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox: stand-alone work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_House_on_Parchment_Street"}
{"title_page": "Soon You'll Get Better", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|2019 song by Taylor Swift featuring Dixie Chicks}}\n{{Infobox song\n|name=Soon You'll Get Better\n|cover=\n|alt=\n|type=\n|artist=[[Taylor Swift]] featuring [[Dixie Chicks]]\n|album=[[Lover (album)|Lover]]\n|released={{Start date|2019|08|23}}\n|format=\n*[[Music download|Digital download]]\n*[[streaming media|streaming]]\n|recorded=\n|studio=\n|genre=[[Country music|Country]]\n|length={{duration|m=3|s=22}}\n|label= [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n|writer=\n*[[Taylor Swift]]\n*[[Jack Antonoff]]\n|producer=\n*Jack Antonoff\n*Taylor Swift\n|misc={{External music video\n| 1 = {{YouTube|tMoW5G5LU08|\"Soon You'll Get Better\"}}\n| header = Audio video\n| type = song\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Soon You'll Get Better'''\" is a song by the American singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]] from her seventh studio album, ''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'', which was released on August 23, 2019, through [[Republic Records]]. It features background vocals from the [[Dixie Chicks]] and was written and produced by Swift and [[Jack Antonoff]]. \n\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" received widespread acclaim from music critics, who praised the vulnerable songwriting and Swift's emotional vocal performance. \"Soon You'll Get Better\" has been described as a [[Country music|country]] ballad and has been compared to \"The Best Day\", a song from Swift's 2008 studio album ''[[Fearless (Taylor Swift album)|Fearless]]'', in both style and in subject matter; both focus on Swift's relationship with her mother.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a28787408/taylor-swift-soon-you-get-better-lyrics-meaning-mom/|title=Taylor Swift's 'Soon You'll Get Better' Lyrics Reveal the Struggle of Watching Her Parents Battle Cancer |last=Feller |first=Madison |date=2019-08-23|website=ELLE|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/soon-youll-get-better/|title=Soon You\u2019ll Get Better: Song Meaning & Easter Eggs|last=Burke|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=Heavy|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> The tone of the song has been compared to [[Prayer|prayers]] and [[Lullaby|lullabies]].\n\nUpon the album's release, \"Soon You'll Get Better\" debuted at number 63 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and became a top 10 hit on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]] chart; the first entry on the chart for the Dixie Chicks, in twelve years. On April 18, 2020, Swift performed a solo piano rendition of the song as part of the ''[[Together at Home|One World: Together At Home]]'' livestream charity event; the performance received universal acclaim from music and television critics.  \n\n== Background and composition ==\nThe song is about the battles Swift's parents have had with [[cancer]], and specifically on her mother's latest diagnosis.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-song-listen-875304/|title=Hear Taylor Swift, Dixie Chicks Team for Heartfelt Song 'Soon You\u2019ll Get Better'|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=2019-08-23|website=Rolling Stone |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> In a live video broadcast on [[YouTube]] the day before the album's release, Swift told fans that the song was the hardest on the album to write, adding that the choice to publish it was made in a family discussion because of how personal it is.<ref name=\":0\" /> Fans who were invited to Swift's Secret Sessions have reported that she left the room when the song played.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" is a [[Country music|country]] [[ballad]]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' call it \"stripped-down\", noting that the only music in the acoustic song is provided by sparse strings,<ref name=\":2\" /> with [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] favorably describing the track as a \"tilt back to [Swift's] country roots\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5659097/taylor-swift-lover-review/|title=Review: On Lover, Taylor Swift Lays Down Her Armor|website=Time|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> and ''[[USA Today]]'' saying it has a \"Nashville feel\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2019/08/23/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-break-your-heart/2066168001/|title=Taylor Swift and Dixie Chicks' new song 'Soon You\u2019ll Get Better' is one of Swift's saddest ever|last=McDermott|first=Maeve|website=USA Today |access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> The song features country trio the Dixie Chicks; a picture of the group was shown in the music video for the album's lead single \"[[Me!]]\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Swift previously performed with the Dixie Chicks shortly after her mother's first cancer diagnosis, and has cited the album [[Fly (Dixie Chicks album)|''Fly'']] as an influence for the production of the ''Lover'' album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-meaning-of-taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-will-break-your-heart-18693155|title=This New Taylor Swift Song Is All About Her Mom, So You'll Want To Grab Some Tissues|website=Bustle|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<nowiki/>'s Raisa Bruner stated that the song is a \"sweet country [[lullaby]]\" and an \"[[Acoustic guitar|acoustic]] ballad about illness and hoping for health\", and added that \"ultimately the song is a kind of [[prayer]]\". Bruner expanded that Swift's repetition of the song title \"functions more as a plea than a proclamation, an uncertainty that the song's delicacy echoes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5651207/taylor-swift-lover-songs-explained/|title=Let's Discuss the Lyrics to Every Song on Taylor Swift's Lover|last=August 24|first=Raisa Bruner|last2=2019|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[New York (magazine)|''Vulture'']]'s Jewly Height noted that Swift's vocal delivery, in the song, is \"hushed as she steers the perspective like a [[cinematographer]] \u2014 first the focus on a tiny detail (\"coat buttons tangled in her hair\"), then a zoomed-out shot of the settings where the trouble's playing out (\"doctors\u2019 offices and hospital rooms\")\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Critical reception ==\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" received widespread critical acclaim, often being noted as a highlight from ''Lover'', with critics praising Swift's \"sincere\" vocal performance, the \"vulnerable\" songwriting and the acoustic instrumentation of the song. \n \n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' has called the song \"heart-wrenching\",<ref name=\":3\" /> with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' saying that it contains the \"most vulnerable lyrics Swift has written in her entire career\".<ref name=\":2\" /> ''USA Today'' said that it ranked among her saddest songs, referring to her previous charity single \"[[Ronan (song)|Ronan]]\", also about cancer.<ref name=\":5\" /> ''Rolling Stone'' complimented that lack of powerful instruments allowed Swift's personal memories to be the focus on the song, with the Dixie Chicks' background vocals serving this further and echoing the internal struggle the lyrics indicate.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''[[USA Today]]'' said that there was no better song on the album for the collaboration.<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' referred to the track as \"a gorgeous, hushed country ballad about [Swift's] mother's illness, bedecked with banjo, fiddle and backing vocals by the Dixie Chicks\" perfect for \"those who think it all went wrong when she left Nashville\" to \"console themselves with\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/23/taylor-swift-lover-review|title=Taylor Swift: Lover review |last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=2019-08-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-23 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[New York (magazine)|''Vulture'']] referred to the song as a \"fingerpicked throwback\" with Swift's singing exhibiting \"breathiness, crisp enunciation, and telegraphed sincerity\". They added that Swift's solo verses repeat a \"modest, wilting pattern with each line over a soft bed of [[acoustic guitar]]\" and that \"the sound gets only slightly bigger at the first chorus, with the introduction of the Chicks' brightening harmonies, gingerly picked [[banjo]], and lyrical [[fiddle]] accents\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-review.html|title=Taylor Swift and the Dixie Chicks Come Full Circle on the Devastating 'Soon You'll Get Better|last=Height|first=Jewly|date=2019-08-23|work=Vulture|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' appreciated the \"jolting specificity\" of Swift's songwriting while stating that the \"agonized\" harmonies from the Dixie Chicks serve as an \"empathetic swaddle\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/arts/music/taylor-swift-lover-review.html|title=Taylor Swift Emerges From the Darkness Unbroken on 'Lover'|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the song a \"heart-rending\" ballad.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/taylor-swift-lover/|title=Taylor Swift Lover|last=Gaca|first=Anna|date=2019-08-26|work=Pitchfork|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[The Spinoff]]'' opined that the song showcases the growth of Swift's vocal delivery and termed it as \"beautiful stuff\", while lauding the Dixie Chicks harmonies as \"literal angels coming around Swift as she grieves her mother's cancer\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/26-08-2019/the-spinoff-reviews-all-18-songs-on-taylor-swifts-lover/|title=The Spinoff reviews all 18 songs on Taylor Swift's Lover|date=2019-08-26|work=The Spinoff|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]''  referred to the song as a \"delicate letter to her mother\", portraying \"the fear and the silence of a hospital room\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/taylor-swift-lover-review-it-s-not-bitter-but-her-grudges-smudge-her-star-power-1.3995116|title=Taylor Swift: Lover review \u2013 It's not bitter but her grudges smudge her star power|last=Bruton|first=Louise|date=2019-08-23|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' wrote that the song has \"the most heavenly harmonies of her [Swift's] career\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/08/album-review-taylor-swift-lover/|title=Taylor Swift Takes the High Road on the More Mature Lover|last=Barr|first=Natalia|date=2019-08-26|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''Saving Country Music'' was complimentary to the track and especially Swift's songwriting; though establishing their review within the context of Swift's long-since departure from the genre of country and their general distaste towards her \"vapid\" output, they say that \"[Swift could] release it to country radio [...] and it would immediately become one of the most country-sounding singles on the format\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.savingcountrymusic.com/taylor-swift-goes-kind-of-country-again-w-soon-youll-get-better/|title=Taylor Swift Goes (Kind Of) Country (Again) w/ \"Soon You\u2019ll Get Better\"|last=Trigger|date=2019-09-03|website=Saving Country Music|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named \"Soon You'll Get Better\" as one of the ten \"most emotionally devastating\" songs of the 2010s decade and stated that the \"heartbreaking\" lyrics showcase Swift's pain and worry effectively. They also labelled the bridge of the song as \"the saddest\" bridge in Swift's discography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2019/12/04/the-most-emotionally-devastating-songs-of-the-2010s/|title=The most emotionally devastating songs of the 2010s|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nUpon the release of ''Lover'', \"Soon You'll Get Better\" debuted at number 63 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] with 10.3 million US streams and 9,000 [[Music download|downloads]] sold. It was Dixie Chicks' first entry on the Hot 100 since \"[[Not Ready to Make Nice]]\" (2007). The song also debuted at number 10 on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]], becoming Swift's 21st top 10 entry and her first since [[Sugarland]]'s \"[[Babe (Sugarland song)|Babe]]\" (2018). For Dixie Chicks, it was their first since \"[[Travelin' Soldier]]\", which reached No. 1 in March 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8528953/taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-hot-country-songs|title=Taylor Swift & Dixie Chicks Debut in Hot Country Songs Top 10 With 'Soon You'll Get Better'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=3 September 2019|accessdate=3 September 2019|first=Jim|last=Asker}}</ref> On the [[Digital Songs|''Billboard'' Digital Song Sales]] chart, the song debuted and peaked at number 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/taylor-swift|title=Digital Song Sales|date=September 7, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, spurred by Swift's debut performance of the song as part of the ''[[Together at Home|One World: Together At Home]]'' live television event, \"Soon You'll Get Better\" was among the top three sellers from the show, along with [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]'s \"[[Carnaval (song)|Carnaval]]\" and [[Kacey Musgraves]]' \"[[Rainbow (Kacey Musgraves song)|Rainbow]]\"; these three songs together accounted for 42% of the total song sales generated by the show. \"Soon You'll Get Better\" sold more than 1000 downloads on April 18, 2020, whereas it sold nil downloads the day before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9361488/one-world-together-at-home-concert-yields-sales-gains-for-taylor-swift-kacey-musgraves-more|title=\u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019 Concert Yields Sales Gains for Taylor Swift, Kacey Musgraves & More|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=2020-04-19|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n== Live performance ==\nOn April 18, 2020, Swift performed a solo piano rendition of \"Soon You'll Get Better\" as part of the [[Lady Gaga]]-curated ''[[Together at Home#Television%20special|One World: Together At Home]]'' television special, a [[Benefit concert|benefit event]] by [[Global Poverty Project#Global%20Citizen|Global Citizen]] to raise funds for the [[World Health Organization]]'s [[COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9361327/one-taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-world-togher-at-home-concert|title=Taylor Swift Sings Heart-Rending 'Soon You'll Get Better' During 'One World' Concert|last=Havens|first=Lyndsey|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The performance received widespread acclaim from [[Music journalism|music]] and [[Television criticism|television critics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-together-at-home-global-citizen-986536/|title=Taylor Swift Delivers Moving 'Soon You'll Get Better' on 'Together at Home' Special|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=April 19, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/taylor-swift-together-at-home-soon-youll-get-better-1234584337/|title=Taylor Swift Performs a Moving Version of 'Soon You'll Get Better' for 'Together at Home'|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=April 19, 2020|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1142326/taylor-swift-provides-hope-with-soon-you-ll-get-better-one-world-concert-performance|title=Taylor Swift Provides Hope With One World Concert Performance|last=Belfiore|first=Emily|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3163734/taylor-swift-one-world-together-at-home-soon-youll-get-better-performance/|title=Taylor Swift's 'Together At Home' Performance Was Pastel Pink Perfection|last=Alston|first=Trey|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[MTV News]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''[[HuffPost]]'' named Swift's performance as the number-one key moment of ''Together At Home'', by stating that Swift moved \"us to tears with her stunning performance\", and added that the track is a \"somber recollection of Taylor's feelings during her mother's battle with cancer, so it's already a heart-wrenching listen, but took on another meaning in the current climate, when so many thousands of people have lost their lives due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/together-at-home-concert-best-moments-key-performances_uk_5e9c18e8c5b6ea335d5ce358|title=Together At Home Concert: 14 Key Moments, From Stunning Performances To Unmade Beds|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|date=April 19, 2020|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nNaming the performance as one of the 10 best moments of the event, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commended that Swift \"effectively ripped our hearts out and reminded us of the power of music to both reflect and ease our pain. It was a tough, lovely and cathartic moment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9361401/one-world-together-at-home-concert-the-10-best-moments|title=&#39;One World: Together at Home&#39;: 10 Best Moments|last=Lynch|first=Joe|date=2020-04-18|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> ''[[Mashable]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/watch-global-citizen-together-at-home-concert-videos/|title=Watch pretty much every star ever perform at the 'Together at Home' concert|last=Marcin|first=Tim|date=April 19, 2020|website=Mashable|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>, ''[[Radio Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-19/one-world-together-highlights/|title=The 8 best moments of the One World: Together at Home concert|last=|first=|date=April 19, 2020|website=Radio Times|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and [[Vogue (magazine)|''Vogue'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/global-citizen-coronavirus-concert-best-performances|title=The 10 Best Performances From the \u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019 Concert|last=Allaire|first=Christian|date=April 20, 2020|website=Vogue|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> also named the performance as one of the best moments of the event. [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] lauded Swift for her song choice, and described: \"It was up to Swift\u2014not usually thought of as a bracingly downbeat figure\u2014who emerged as sober truth-teller at nearly the last minute, appearing alone, mirrored by her piano top, to perform a song she may be unlikely to sing under any other circumstance outside the studio\". It further expanded that, \"with verses so distraught they threaten to betray the deceptively optimist title as magical thinking\", \"there couldn't have been a more appropriate song for all the families of [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] patients sitting at home. The upturn in Swift's mouth as she wrapped up her appearance was measured in micro-millimeters, as it should be\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/one-world-together-at-home-tv-review-taylor-swift-rolling-stones-lady-gaga-1234584371/|title=\u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019: TV Review|last=Willman|first=Chris|last2=|first2=|date=2020-04-19|website=Variety|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/115983325|title=''Lover'' by Taylor Swift|last=|first=|date=August 23, 2019|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|location=United States|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* [[Taylor Swift]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, songwriter, producer\n* [[Jack Antonoff]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer, songwriter, acoustic guitar, keyboards, piano, recording engineer, studio personnel\n* [[Dixie Chicks]]&nbsp;\u2013 featured vocals, backing vocals\n* [[Emily Strayer]] \u2013 banjo\n* [[Martie Maguire]] \u2013 fiddle\n* Laura Sisk &nbsp;\u2013 recording engineer, studio personnel\n* John Rooney&nbsp;\u2013 assistant recording engineer, studio personnel\n* John Hanes&nbsp;\u2013 mix engineer, studio personnel\n* Serban Ghenea&nbsp;\u2013 mixer, studio personnel\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/08/aria-chart-watch-540/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #540|publisher=auspOp|date=August 31, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| 54\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|71|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|97|date=20190830|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|63|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|10|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2019-08-29/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| 31\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| August 23, 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| align=\"center\"|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|Taylor-Swift|Soon-Youll-Get-Better}}\n\n\n{{Taylor Swift songs}}\n{{Dixie Chicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soon You'll Get Better (song)}}\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Taylor Swift songs]]\n[[Category:Dixie Chicks songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Taylor Swift]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jack Antonoff]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jack Antonoff]]\n[[Category:Songs about diseases and disorders]]\n[[Category:Country ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Taylor Swift]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|2019 song by Taylor Swift featuring Dixie Chicks}}\n{{Infobox song\n|name=Soon You'll Get Better\n|cover=\n|alt=\n|type=\n|artist=[[Taylor Swift]] featuring [[Dixie Chicks]]\n|album=[[Lover (album)|Lover]]\n|released={{Start date|2019|08|23}}\n|format=\n*[[Music download|Digital download]]\n*[[streaming media|streaming]]\n|recorded=\n|studio=\n|genre=[[Country music|Country]]\n|length={{duration|m=3|s=22}}\n|label= [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n|writer=\n*[[Taylor Swift]]\n*[[Jack Antonoff]]\n|producer=\n*Jack Antonoff\n*Taylor Swift\n|misc={{External music video\n| 1 = {{YouTube|tMoW5G5LU08|\"Soon You'll Get Better\"}}\n| header = Audio video\n| type = song\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Soon You'll Get Better'''\" is a song by the American singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]] from her seventh studio album, ''[[Lover (album)|Lover]]'', which was released on August 23, 2019, through [[Republic Records]]. It features background vocals from the [[Dixie Chicks]] and was written and produced by Swift and [[Jack Antonoff]]. \n\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" received widespread acclaim from music critics, who praised the vulnerable songwriting and Swift's emotional vocal performance. \"Soon You'll Get Better\" has been described as a [[Country music|country]] ballad and has been compared to \"The Best Day\", a song from Swift's 2008 studio album ''[[Fearless (Taylor Swift album)|Fearless]]'', in both style and in subject matter; both focus on Swift's relationship with her mother.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a28787408/taylor-swift-soon-you-get-better-lyrics-meaning-mom/|title=Taylor Swift's 'Soon You'll Get Better' Lyrics Reveal the Struggle of Watching Her Parents Battle Cancer |last=Feller |first=Madison |date=2019-08-23|website=ELLE|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/08/soon-youll-get-better/|title=Soon You\u2019ll Get Better: Song Meaning & Easter Eggs|last=Burke|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=Heavy|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> The tone of the song has been compared to [[Prayer|prayers]] and [[Lullaby|lullabies]].\n\nUpon the album's release, \"Soon You'll Get Better\" debuted at number 63 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and became a top 10 hit on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]] chart; the first entry on the chart for the Dixie Chicks, in twelve years. On April 18, 2020, Swift performed a solo piano rendition of the song as part of the ''[[Together at Home|One World: Together At Home]]'' livestream charity event; the performance received universal acclaim from music and television critics.  \n\n== Background and composition ==\nThe song is about the battles Swift's parents have had with [[cancer]], and specifically on her mother's latest diagnosis.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-song-listen-875304/|title=Hear Taylor Swift, Dixie Chicks Team for Heartfelt Song 'Soon You\u2019ll Get Better'|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=2019-08-23|website=Rolling Stone |archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> In a live video broadcast on [[YouTube]] the day before the album's release, Swift told fans that the song was the hardest on the album to write, adding that the choice to publish it was made in a family discussion because of how personal it is.<ref name=\":0\" /> Fans who were invited to Swift's Secret Sessions have reported that she left the room when the song played.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" is a [[Country music|country]] [[ballad]]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' call it \"stripped-down\", noting that the only music in the acoustic song is provided by sparse strings,<ref name=\":2\" /> with [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] favorably describing the track as a \"tilt back to [Swift's] country roots\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5659097/taylor-swift-lover-review/|title=Review: On Lover, Taylor Swift Lays Down Her Armor|website=Time|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> and ''[[USA Today]]'' saying it has a \"Nashville feel\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2019/08/23/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-break-your-heart/2066168001/|title=Taylor Swift and Dixie Chicks' new song 'Soon You\u2019ll Get Better' is one of Swift's saddest ever|last=McDermott|first=Maeve|website=USA Today |access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> The song features country trio the Dixie Chicks; a picture of the group was shown in the music video for the album's lead single \"[[Me!]]\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Swift previously performed with the Dixie Chicks shortly after her mother's first cancer diagnosis, and has cited the album [[Fly (Dixie Chicks album)|''Fly'']] as an influence for the production of the ''Lover'' album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-meaning-of-taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-will-break-your-heart-18693155|title=This New Taylor Swift Song Is All About Her Mom, So You'll Want To Grab Some Tissues|website=Bustle|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<nowiki/>'s Raisa Bruner stated that the song is a \"sweet country [[lullaby]]\" and an \"[[Acoustic guitar|acoustic]] ballad about illness and hoping for health\", and added that \"ultimately the song is a kind of [[prayer]]\". Bruner expanded that Swift's repetition of the song title \"functions more as a plea than a proclamation, an uncertainty that the song's delicacy echoes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5651207/taylor-swift-lover-songs-explained/|title=Let's Discuss the Lyrics to Every Song on Taylor Swift's Lover|last=August 24|first=Raisa Bruner|last2=2019|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[New York (magazine)|''Vulture'']]'s Jewly Height noted that Swift's vocal delivery, in the song, is \"hushed as she steers the perspective like a [[cinematographer]] \u2014 first the focus on a tiny detail (\"coat buttons tangled in her hair\"), then a zoomed-out shot of the settings where the trouble's playing out (\"doctors\u2019 offices and hospital rooms\")\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Critical reception ==\n\"Soon You'll Get Better\" received widespread critical acclaim, often being noted as a highlight from ''Lover'', with critics praising Swift's \"sincere\" vocal performance, the \"vulnerable\" songwriting and the acoustic instrumentation of the song. \n \n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' has called the song \"heart-wrenching\",<ref name=\":3\" /> with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' saying that it contains the \"most vulnerable lyrics Swift has written in her entire career\".<ref name=\":2\" /> ''USA Today'' said that it ranked among her saddest songs, referring to her previous charity single \"[[Ronan (song)|Ronan]]\", also about cancer.<ref name=\":5\" /> ''Rolling Stone'' complimented that lack of powerful instruments allowed Swift's personal memories to be the focus on the song, with the Dixie Chicks' background vocals serving this further and echoing the internal struggle the lyrics indicate.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''[[USA Today]]'' said that there was no better song on the album for the collaboration.<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' referred to the track as \"a gorgeous, hushed country ballad about [Swift's] mother's illness, bedecked with banjo, fiddle and backing vocals by the Dixie Chicks\" perfect for \"those who think it all went wrong when she left Nashville\" to \"console themselves with\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/23/taylor-swift-lover-review|title=Taylor Swift: Lover review |last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=2019-08-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-23 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[New York (magazine)|''Vulture'']] referred to the song as a \"fingerpicked throwback\" with Swift's singing exhibiting \"breathiness, crisp enunciation, and telegraphed sincerity\". They added that Swift's solo verses repeat a \"modest, wilting pattern with each line over a soft bed of [[acoustic guitar]]\" and that \"the sound gets only slightly bigger at the first chorus, with the introduction of the Chicks' brightening harmonies, gingerly picked [[banjo]], and lyrical [[fiddle]] accents\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/taylor-swift-dixie-chicks-soon-youll-get-better-review.html|title=Taylor Swift and the Dixie Chicks Come Full Circle on the Devastating 'Soon You'll Get Better|last=Height|first=Jewly|date=2019-08-23|work=Vulture|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' appreciated the \"jolting specificity\" of Swift's songwriting while stating that the \"agonized\" harmonies from the Dixie Chicks serve as an \"empathetic swaddle\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/arts/music/taylor-swift-lover-review.html|title=Taylor Swift Emerges From the Darkness Unbroken on 'Lover'|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called the song a \"heart-rending\" ballad.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/taylor-swift-lover/|title=Taylor Swift Lover|last=Gaca|first=Anna|date=2019-08-26|work=Pitchfork|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[The Spinoff]]'' opined that the song showcases the growth of Swift's vocal delivery and termed it as \"beautiful stuff\", while lauding the Dixie Chicks harmonies as \"literal angels coming around Swift as she grieves her mother's cancer\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/26-08-2019/the-spinoff-reviews-all-18-songs-on-taylor-swifts-lover/|title=The Spinoff reviews all 18 songs on Taylor Swift's Lover|date=2019-08-26|work=The Spinoff|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]''  referred to the song as a \"delicate letter to her mother\", portraying \"the fear and the silence of a hospital room\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/taylor-swift-lover-review-it-s-not-bitter-but-her-grudges-smudge-her-star-power-1.3995116|title=Taylor Swift: Lover review \u2013 It's not bitter but her grudges smudge her star power|last=Bruton|first=Louise|date=2019-08-23|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' wrote that the song has \"the most heavenly harmonies of her [Swift's] career\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/08/album-review-taylor-swift-lover/|title=Taylor Swift Takes the High Road on the More Mature Lover|last=Barr|first=Natalia|date=2019-08-26|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> ''Saving Country Music'' was complimentary to the track and especially Swift's songwriting; though establishing their review within the context of Swift's long-since departure from the genre of country and their general distaste towards her \"vapid\" output, they say that \"[Swift could] release it to country radio [...] and it would immediately become one of the most country-sounding singles on the format\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.savingcountrymusic.com/taylor-swift-goes-kind-of-country-again-w-soon-youll-get-better/|title=Taylor Swift Goes (Kind Of) Country (Again) w/ \"Soon You\u2019ll Get Better\"|last=Trigger|date=2019-09-03|website=Saving Country Music|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named \"Soon You'll Get Better\" as one of the ten \"most emotionally devastating\" songs of the 2010s decade and stated that the \"heartbreaking\" lyrics showcase Swift's pain and worry effectively. They also labelled the bridge of the song as \"the saddest\" bridge in Swift's discography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2019/12/04/the-most-emotionally-devastating-songs-of-the-2010s/|title=The most emotionally devastating songs of the 2010s|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nUpon the release of ''Lover'', \"Soon You'll Get Better\" debuted at number 63 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] with 10.3 million US streams and 9,000 [[Music download|downloads]] sold. It was Dixie Chicks' first entry on the Hot 100 since \"[[Not Ready to Make Nice]]\" (2007). The song also debuted at number 10 on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]], becoming Swift's 21st top 10 entry and her first since [[Sugarland]]'s \"[[Babe (Sugarland song)|Babe]]\" (2018). For Dixie Chicks, it was their first since \"[[Travelin' Soldier]]\", which reached No. 1 in March 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8528953/taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-hot-country-songs|title=Taylor Swift & Dixie Chicks Debut in Hot Country Songs Top 10 With 'Soon You'll Get Better'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=3 September 2019|accessdate=3 September 2019|first=Jim|last=Asker}}</ref> On the [[Digital Songs|''Billboard'' Digital Song Sales]] chart, the song debuted and peaked at number 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/taylor-swift|title=Digital Song Sales|date=September 7, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, spurred by Swift's debut performance of the song as part of the ''[[Together at Home|One World: Together At Home]]'' live television event, \"Soon You'll Get Better\" was among the top three sellers from the show, along with [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]'s \"[[Carnaval (song)|Carnaval]]\" and [[Kacey Musgraves]]' \"[[Rainbow (Kacey Musgraves song)|Rainbow]]\"; these three songs together accounted for 42% of the total song sales generated by the show. \"Soon You'll Get Better\" sold more than 1000 downloads on April 18, 2020, whereas it sold nil downloads the day before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9361488/one-world-together-at-home-concert-yields-sales-gains-for-taylor-swift-kacey-musgraves-more|title=\u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019 Concert Yields Sales Gains for Taylor Swift, Kacey Musgraves & More|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=2020-04-19|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n== Live performance ==\nOn April 18, 2020, Swift performed a solo piano rendition of \"Soon You'll Get Better\" as part of the [[Lady Gaga]]-curated ''[[Together at Home#Television%20special|One World: Together At Home]]'' television special, a [[Benefit concert|benefit event]] by [[Global Poverty Project#Global%20Citizen|Global Citizen]] to raise funds for the [[World Health Organization]]'s [[COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9361327/one-taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-world-togher-at-home-concert|title=Taylor Swift Sings Heart-Rending 'Soon You'll Get Better' During 'One World' Concert|last=Havens|first=Lyndsey|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The performance received widespread acclaim from [[Music journalism|music]] and [[Television criticism|television critics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylor-swift-soon-youll-get-better-together-at-home-global-citizen-986536/|title=Taylor Swift Delivers Moving 'Soon You'll Get Better' on 'Together at Home' Special|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=April 19, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/taylor-swift-together-at-home-soon-youll-get-better-1234584337/|title=Taylor Swift Performs a Moving Version of 'Soon You'll Get Better' for 'Together at Home'|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=April 19, 2020|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1142326/taylor-swift-provides-hope-with-soon-you-ll-get-better-one-world-concert-performance|title=Taylor Swift Provides Hope With One World Concert Performance|last=Belfiore|first=Emily|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3163734/taylor-swift-one-world-together-at-home-soon-youll-get-better-performance/|title=Taylor Swift's 'Together At Home' Performance Was Pastel Pink Perfection|last=Alston|first=Trey|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[MTV News]]|url-status=live|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''[[HuffPost]]'' named Swift's performance as the number-one key moment of ''Together At Home'', by stating that Swift moved \"us to tears with her stunning performance\", and added that the track is a \"somber recollection of Taylor's feelings during her mother's battle with cancer, so it's already a heart-wrenching listen, but took on another meaning in the current climate, when so many thousands of people have lost their lives due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/together-at-home-concert-best-moments-key-performances_uk_5e9c18e8c5b6ea335d5ce358|title=Together At Home Concert: 14 Key Moments, From Stunning Performances To Unmade Beds|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|date=April 19, 2020|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Naming the performance as one of the 10 best moments of the event, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commended that Swift \"effectively ripped our hearts out and reminded us of the power of music to both reflect and ease our pain. It was a tough, lovely and cathartic moment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9361401/one-world-together-at-home-concert-the-10-best-moments|title=&#39;One World: Together at Home&#39;: 10 Best Moments|last=Lynch|first=Joe|date=2020-04-18|website=Billboard|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> ''[[Mashable]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/watch-global-citizen-together-at-home-concert-videos/|title=Watch pretty much every star ever perform at the 'Together at Home' concert|last=Marcin|first=Tim|date=April 19, 2020|website=Mashable|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>, ''[[Radio Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-19/one-world-together-highlights/|title=The 8 best moments of the One World: Together at Home concert|last=|first=|date=April 19, 2020|website=Radio Times|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and [[Vogue (magazine)|''Vogue'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/global-citizen-coronavirus-concert-best-performances|title=The 10 Best Performances From the \u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019 Concert|last=Allaire|first=Christian|date=April 20, 2020|website=Vogue|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> also named the performance as one of the best moments of the event. [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] lauded Swift for her song choice, and described: \"It was up to Swift\u2014not usually thought of as a bracingly downbeat figure\u2014who emerged as sober truth-teller at nearly the last minute, appearing alone, mirrored by her piano top, to perform a song she may be unlikely to sing under any other circumstance outside the studio\". It further expanded that, \"with verses so distraught they threaten to betray the deceptively optimist title as magical thinking\", \"there couldn't have been a more appropriate song for all the families of [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] patients sitting at home. The upturn in Swift's mouth as she wrapped up her appearance was measured in micro-millimeters, as it should be\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/one-world-together-at-home-tv-review-taylor-swift-rolling-stones-lady-gaga-1234584371/|title=\u2018One World: Together at Home\u2019: TV Review|last=Willman|first=Chris|last2=|first2=|date=2020-04-19|website=Variety|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/115983325|title=''Lover'' by Taylor Swift|last=|first=|date=August 23, 2019|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|location=United States|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* [[Taylor Swift]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, songwriter, producer\n* [[Jack Antonoff]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer, songwriter, acoustic guitar, keyboards, piano, recording engineer, studio personnel\n* [[Dixie Chicks]]&nbsp;\u2013 featured vocals, backing vocals\n* [[Emily Strayer]] \u2013 banjo\n* [[Martie Maguire]] \u2013 fiddle\n* Laura Sisk &nbsp;\u2013 recording engineer, studio personnel\n* John Rooney&nbsp;\u2013 assistant recording engineer, studio personnel\n* John Hanes&nbsp;\u2013 mix engineer, studio personnel\n* Serban Ghenea&nbsp;\u2013 mixer, studio personnel\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/08/aria-chart-watch-540/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #540|publisher=auspOp|date=August 31, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| 54\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|71|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|97|date=20190830|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|63|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|10|artist=Taylor Swift|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2019-08-29/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| 31\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| August 23, 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| align=\"center\"|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|Taylor-Swift|Soon-Youll-Get-Better}}\n\n\n{{Taylor Swift songs}}\n{{Dixie Chicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soon You'll Get Better (song)}}\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:2010s ballads]]\n[[Category:Taylor Swift songs]]\n[[Category:Dixie Chicks songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Taylor Swift]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jack Antonoff]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jack Antonoff]]\n[[Category:Songs about diseases and disorders]]\n[[Category:Country ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Taylor Swift]]\n", "name_user": "Rfl0216", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLive performance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soon_You%27ll_Get_Better"}
{"title_page": "Erketu", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of reptiles (fossil)}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Late Cretaceous]], {{fossilrange|102|86}}\n| image = Erketu.jpg\n| image_caption = Cervical vertebrae of the holotype IGM 100/1803 in lateral view\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| display_parents = 2\n| taxon = Erketu\n| authority = Ksepka & Norell 2006\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Erketu ellisoni'''''\n| type_species_authority = Ksepka & Norell 2006\n}}\n\n'''''Erketu''''' (meaning \"Erket\u00fc Tengri\") is a genus of [[somphospondylan]] [[sauropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in [[Asia]] during the [[Late Cretaceous]] roughly between 102 million and 86 million years ago. Its fossils were found in Mongolia between 2002 and 2003 during a field expedition and first described in 2006; later on in 2010 due to some cervicals that were left behind in the expedition. ''Erketu'' represent one of the first sauropods described from the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]]. The elongated cervical vertebrae of ''Erketu'' seems to indicate that it was the sauropod with the longest neck relative to its body size.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\nThe first remains of ''Erketu'' were found back in 2002 by the American Museum of Natural History\u2013Mongolian Academy of Sciences expedition conducted in [[Mongolia]]. The team discovered the outcrops of the new locality Bor Guv\u00e9, which overlies the Khara Kuthul locality and therefore is referable to the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]]. The unearthed specimen, '''IGM 100/1803''', was found in exposure at the sediments of Bor Guv\u00e9, mainly composed by [[sandstone]] and [[interbedded]] grey [[siltstones]], suggesting a [[fluvial]] environment that is consistent with the Bayan Shireh Formation. Collected elements are mainly represented by [[cervical vertebrae]] and postcranial remains, such as the partial right [[sternum]], [[tibia]] and [[fibula]] with [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#astragalus|astragalus]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#calcaneum|calcaneum]].<ref name=Ksepka2006>{{cite journal|first1=D. T.|last1=Ksepka|first2=M. A.|last2=Norell|year=2006|title=Erketu ellisoni, a long-necked sauropod from Bor Guv\u00e9 (Dornogov Aimag, Mongolia)|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=3508|pages=1\u221216|hdl=2246/5783|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/5783/N3508.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n\nThe remains became the [[holotype]] for the new genus and species ''Erketu ellisoni'', first described in [[2006 in paleontology|2006]] by Daniel Ksepka and [[Mark Norell]] of the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. The generic name of this particular sauropod species is named after the creator god (tengri) of the Mongolian [[shamanism]], '''Erket\u00fc'''. The specific name, ''ellisoni'', is in honor to the American Museum of Natural History's senior principal [[paleoartist]], and close friend of Norell: Mick Ellison.<ref name=Ksepka2006/> In 2003 the team returned to the site and recovered three additional cervicals that were left behind during the first field expedition, and consequently described in [[2010 in paleontology|2010]].<ref name=Ksepka2010>{{cite journal|last1=Ksepka|first1=D. T.|last2=Norell|first2=M. A.|year=2010|title=The Illusory Evidence for Asian Brachiosauridae: New Material of Erketu ellisoni and a Phylogenetic Reappraisal of Basal Titanosauriformes|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/6087/N3700.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=3700|hdl=2246/6087|doi=10.1206/3700.2}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Sauropodomorpha cervical muscles.png|thumb|left|Comparison between the cervicals of ''Erketu'' and other [[sauropodomorphs]]]]\n[[File:Erketu Scale.svg|thumb|Size comparison with a human]]\n\n''Erketu'' was a relatively large sauropod, with an estimated length of {{convert|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{convert|5|t|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Paul2016>{{cite book|last1=Paul|first1=G. S.|title=The Princeton Field Guide to Dinosaurs|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2016|isbn=9780691167664|edition=2nd|location=Princeton, New Jersey|pages=223\u2212224}}</ref> Its neck was estimated to be twice as long as its body, which may be a record for neck to body ratio. The exact ratio is unknown, because no [[dorsal vertebrae]] of ''E. ellisoni'' have been reported, although some hindlimb material suggests the approximate size of the body. The long neck of ''Erketu'' is the result of the individual vertebrae being greatly elongated; it is unknown if the number of cervical vertebrae was increased. ''Erketu'' is also diagnosed by bifurcate anterior cervical neural spines, another unusual trait for a titanosauriform. The preserved cervicals include the [[Atlas (anatomy)|atlas]], [[Axis (anatomy)|axis]] and C3 to C9, however, the sixth is missing, giving a total of eight preserved cervical vertebrae.<ref name=Ksepka2006/><ref name=Ksepka2010/>\n\nThe preserved sternum is rather thickened at some borders and shows a very deep lateral edge, it measures about {{convert|530|mm|cm|abbr=on}} long. The right hindlimb elements were nicely found in articulation and they resemble those of ''[[Gobititan]]''. The tibia is very straight, measuring {{convert|710|mm|cm|abbr=on}} in total length, it has slightly expanded ends and in comparison to that of ''[[Opisthocoelicaudia]]'', the anterior and distal expansions are not very developed. The fibula is longer than the tibia with a length of {{convert|750|mm|cm|abbr=on}}, however, it appears to be broken on the distal end of one of the [[Tubercle (bone)|trochanters]].<ref name=Ksepka2006/>\n\n==Classification==\nThe phylogenetic analysis of sauropods performed by its describers indicates that ''Erketu'' is a basal somphospondylian (the [[clade]] of all [[macronarians]] closer to [[titanosaurs]] than to [[brachiosaurids]]), and is most closely related to [[Titanosauria]], being a close relative of ''[[Euhelopus]]''.<ref name=Ksepka2006/>\n\nDuring the description of ''[[Europatitan]]'' in 2017, a new cladistic analysis was performed. Here, ''Erketu'' was recovered in a [[polytomy]] along ''[[Chubutisaurus]]'' within the Somphospondyli:<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fern\u00e1ndez-Baldor|first1=F. T.|last2=Canudo|first2=J. I.|last3=Huerta|first3=P.|last4=Moreno-Azanza|first4=M.|last5=Montero|first5=D.|date=2017|title=Europatitan eastwoodi, a new sauropod from the lower Cretaceous of Iberia in the initial radiation of somphospondylans in Laurasia|journal=PeerJ|volume=5|pages=e3409|doi=10.7717/peerj.3409|doi-access=free|pmc=5490465|pmid=28674644}}</ref>\n{{clade|style=font-size:100%; line-height:100%;\n|label1=[[Somphospondyli]]\n|1={{clade\n|1=''[[Europatitan|Europatitan eastwoodi]]''\n|2=''[[Tendaguria|Tendaguria tanzaniensis]]''\n|3={{clade\n|1=''[[Sauroposeidon|Sauroposeidon proteles]]\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Chubutisaurus|Chubutisaurus insignis]]''\n|2='''''Erketu ellisoni'''''\n|3={{clade\n|1={{clade\n|1={{clade\n|1=[[Titanosauria]]}} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n==Paleoecology==\nThe remains of ''Erketu'' are attributed to the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]],<ref name=Ksepka2010/> which is believed to have been dominated by fluvial and lacrustine environments, such as large [[meanders]] and [[lakes]] but also a notorius semi-arid climate.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ishigaki|first1=S.|last2=Tsogtbaatar|first2=K.|last3=Saneyoshi|first3=M.|last4=Mainbayar|first4=B.|last5=Aoki|first5=K.|last6=Ulziitseren|first6=S.|last7=Imayama|first7=T.|last8=Takahashi|first8=A.|last9=Toyoda|first9=S.|last10=Bayardorj|first10=C.|last11=Buyantegsh|first11=B.|last12=Batsukh|first12=J.|last13=Purevsuren|first13=B.|last14=Asai|first14=H.|last15=Tsutanaga|first15=S.|last16=Fujii|first16=K.|date=2016|title=Report of the Okayama University of Science - Mongolian Institute of Paleontology and Geology Joint Expedition in 2016|journal=Bulletin of Research Institute of Natural Sciences|issue=42|pages=33\u221246|url=http://dinosaur.ous.ac.jp/pdf/box/exc2016.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Slowiak|first1=J.|last2=Szczygielski|first2=T.|last3=Ginter|first3=M.|last4=Fostowicz-Frelik|first4=L.|date=2020|title=Uninterrupted growth in a non\u2010polar hadrosaur explains the gigantism among duck\u2010billed dinosaurs|journal=Paleontology|doi=10.1111/pala.12473}}</ref> The age is estimated to be around 102 million and 86 million years ago, [[Cenomanian]] to [[Santonian]] epochs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Danilov|first1=I. G.|last2=Hirayama|first2=R.|last3=Sukhanov|first3=V. B.|last4=Suzuki|first4=S.|last5=Watabe|first5=M.|last6=Vitek|first6=N. S.|title=Cretaceous soft-shelled turtles (Trionychidae) of Mongolia: new diversity, records and a revision|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|date=2014|volume=12|issue=7|doi=10.1080/14772019.2013.847870}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kurumada|first1=Y.|last2=Aoki|first2=S.|last3=Aoki|first3=K.|last4=Kato|first4=D.|last5=Saneyoshi|first5=M.|last6=Tsogtbaatar|first6=K.|last7=Windley|first7=B. F.|last8=Ishigaki|first8=S.|title=Calcite U\u2013Pb age of the Cretaceous vertebrate\u2010bearing Bayn Shire Formation in the Eastern Gobi Desert of Mongolia: usefulness of caliche for age determination|journal=Terra Nova|date=2020|doi=10.1111/ter.12456}}</ref> Here, ''Erketu'' lived alongside diverse dinosaur fauna, such as the predators ''[[Achillobator]]''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Perle|first1=A.|last2=Norell|first2=M. A.|last3=Clark|first3=J.|date=1999|title=A new maniraptoran Theropod\u2212Achillobator giganticus (Dromaeosauridae)\u2212from the Upper Cretaceous of Burkhant, Mongolia|journal=Contributions from the Geology and Mineralogy Chair, National Museum of Mongolia|issue=101|pages=1\u2013105|oclc=69865262}}</ref> and potentially ''[[Alectrosaurus]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Perle|first1=A.|title=O pervoy nakhodke Alektrozavra (Tyrannosauridae, Theropoda) iz pozdnego Mela Mongolii|trans-title=On the first discovery of Alectrosaurus (Tyrannosauridae, Theropoda) in the Late Cretaceous of Mongolia|journal=Shinzhlekh Ukhaany Akademi Geologiin Khureelen|year=1977|volume=3|issue=3|pages=104\u2013113|language=Russian}}</ref> the abundant hadrosauroid ''[[Gobihadros]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tsogtbaatar|first1=K.|last2=Weishampel|first2=D. B.|last3=Evans|first3=D. C.|last4=Watabe|first4=M.|date=2019|title=A new hadrosauroid (Dinosauria: Ornithopoda) from the Late Cretaceous Baynshire Formation of the Gobi Desert (Mongolia)|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=14|issue=4|pages=e0208480|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0208480|doi-access=free|pmid=30995236|pmc=6469754|bibcode=2019PLoSO..1408480T}}</ref> heavy armored ''[[Talarurus]]'' and ''[[Tsagantegia]]'',<ref name=Park2020>{{cite journal|last1=Park|first1=J.|last4=Kobayashi|first4=Y.|last5=Koppelhus|first5=E.|last6=Barsbold|first6=R.|last7=Mateus|first7=O.|last8=Lee|first8=S.|last9=Kim|first9=S. H.|title=Additional skulls of Talarurus plicatospineus (Dinosauria: Ankylosauridae) and implications for paleobiogeography and paleoecology of armored dinosaurs|date=2020|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=108|pages=e104340|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104340}}</ref> and the well-known therizinosaurs ''[[Erlikosaurus]]'' and ''[[Segnosaurus]]''.<ref name=Zanno2016>{{cite journal|last1=Zanno|first1=L. E.|last2=Tsogtbaatar|first2=K.|last3=Chinzorig|first3=T.|last4=Gates|first4=T. A.|title=Specializations of the mandibular anatomy and dentition of Segnosaurus galbinensis (Theropoda: Therizinosauria)|year=2016|journal=PeerJ|volume=4|pages=e1885|doi=10.7717/peerj.1885|doi-access=free|pmid=27069815|pmc=4824891}}</ref> The locality of ''Erketu'' has also yielded an indeterminate/unnamed titanosaur and very abundant fossilized [[fruits]].<ref name=Ksepka2006/><ref name=Ksepka2010/> Some ecological niches were filled by several dinosaurs, such as the [[Browsing (herbivory)|browsers]] ''Erlikosaurus'', ''Segnosaurus''<ref name=Zanno2016/> and Tsagantegia; in contrast, ''Talarurus'' was a [[Grazing (behaviour)|grazer]].<ref name=Park2020/> ''Erketu'' in the other hand, due to its very long neck, was likely a high browser.<ref name=Paul2016/>\n\n[[File:Bayan Shireh Formation Fauna.png|thumb|center|400px|''Erketu'' compared to the known [[Dinosauria]] of the Bayan Shireh Formation (''Erketu'' in brown, next to ''Gobihadros'')]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs|Cretaceous}}\n* [[Mark Norell]]\n* [[Sauropod neck posture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sauropodomorpha|M.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q138872}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2006]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Mongolia]]\n[[Category:Macronarians]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Mark Norell]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of reptiles (fossil)}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Late Cretaceous]], {{fossilrange|102|86}}\n| image = Erketu.jpg\n| image_caption = Cervical vertebrae of the holotype IGM 100/1803 in lateral view\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| display_parents = 2\n| taxon = Erketu\n| authority = Ksepka & Norell 2006\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Erketu ellisoni'''''\n| type_species_authority = Ksepka & Norell 2006\n}}\n\n'''''Erketu''''' (meaning \"Erket\u00fc Tengri\") is a genus of [[somphospondylan]] [[sauropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in [[Asia]] during the [[Late Cretaceous]] roughly between 102 million and 86 million years ago. Its fossils were found in Mongolia between 2002 and 2003 during a field expedition and first described in 2006; later on in 2010 due to some cervicals that were left behind in the expedition. ''Erketu'' represent one of the first sauropods described from the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]]. The elongated cervical vertebrae of ''Erketu'' seems to indicate that it was the sauropod with the longest neck relative to its body size.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\nThe first remains of ''Erketu'' were found back in 2002 by the American Museum of Natural History\u2013Mongolian Academy of Sciences expedition conducted in [[Mongolia]]. The team discovered the outcrops of the new locality Bor Guv\u00e9, which overlies the Khara Kuthul locality and therefore is referable to the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]]. The unearthed specimen, '''IGM 100/1803''', was found in exposure at the sediments of Bor Guv\u00e9, mainly composed by [[sandstone]] and [[interbedded]] grey [[siltstones]], suggesting a [[fluvial]] environment that is consistent with the Bayan Shireh Formation. Collected elements are mainly represented by [[cervical vertebrae]] and postcranial remains, such as the partial right [[sternum]], [[tibia]] and [[fibula]] with [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#astragalus|astragalus]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#calcaneum|calcaneum]].<ref name=Ksepka2006>{{cite journal|first1=D. T.|last1=Ksepka|first2=M. A.|last2=Norell|year=2006|title=Erketu ellisoni, a long-necked sauropod from Bor Guv\u00e9 (Dornogov Aimag, Mongolia)|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=3508|pages=1\u221216|hdl=2246/5783|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/5783/N3508.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n\nThe remains became the [[holotype]] for the new genus and species ''Erketu ellisoni'', first described in [[2006 in paleontology|2006]] by Daniel Ksepka and [[Mark Norell]] of the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. The generic name of this particular sauropod species is named after the creator god (tengri) of the Mongolian [[shamanism]], '''Erket\u00fc'''. The specific name, ''ellisoni'', is in honor to the American Museum of Natural History's senior principal [[paleoartist]], and close friend of Norell: Mick Ellison.<ref name=Ksepka2006/> In 2003 the team returned to the site and recovered three additional cervicals that were left behind during the first field expedition, and consequently described in [[2010 in paleontology|2010]].<ref name=Ksepka2010>{{cite journal|last1=Ksepka|first1=D. T.|last2=Norell|first2=M. A.|year=2010|title=The Illusory Evidence for Asian Brachiosauridae: New Material of Erketu ellisoni and a Phylogenetic Reappraisal of Basal Titanosauriformes|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/6087/N3700.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=3700|hdl=2246/6087|doi=10.1206/3700.2}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Sauropodomorpha cervical muscles.png|thumb|left|Comparison between the cervicals of ''Erketu'' and other [[sauropodomorphs]]]]\n[[File:Erketu Scale.svg|thumb|Size comparison with a human]]\n\n''Erketu'' was a relatively large sauropod, with an estimated length of {{convert|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{convert|5|t|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Paul2016>{{cite book|last1=Paul|first1=G. S.|title=The Princeton Field Guide to Dinosaurs|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2016|isbn=9780691167664|edition=2nd|location=Princeton, New Jersey|pages=223\u2212224}}</ref> Its neck was estimated to be twice as long as its body, which may be a record for neck to body ratio. The exact ratio is unknown, because no [[dorsal vertebrae]] of ''E. ellisoni'' have been reported, although some hindlimb material suggests the approximate size of the body. The long neck of ''Erketu'' is the result of the individual vertebrae being greatly elongated; it is unknown if the number of cervical vertebrae was increased. ''Erketu'' is also diagnosed by bifurcate anterior cervical neural spines, another unusual trait for a titanosauriform. The preserved cervicals include the [[Atlas (anatomy)|atlas]], [[Axis (anatomy)|axis]] and C3 to C9, however, the sixth is missing, giving a total of eight preserved cervical vertebrae.<ref name=Ksepka2006/><ref name=Ksepka2010/>\n\nThe preserved sternum is rather thickened at some borders and shows a very deep lateral edge, it measures about {{convert|530|mm|cm|abbr=on}} long. The right hindlimb elements were nicely found in articulation and they resemble those of ''[[Gobititan]]''. The tibia is very straight, measuring {{convert|710|mm|cm|abbr=on}} in total length, it has slightly expanded ends and in comparison to that of ''[[Opisthocoelicaudia]]'', the anterior and distal expansions are not very developed. The fibula is longer than the tibia with a length of {{convert|750|mm|cm|abbr=on}}, however, it appears to be broken on the distal end of one of the [[Tubercle (bone)|trochanters]].<ref name=Ksepka2006/>\n\n==Classification==\nThe phylogenetic analysis of sauropods performed by its describers indicates that ''Erketu'' is a basal somphospondylian (the [[clade]] of all [[macronarians]] closer to [[titanosaurs]] than to [[brachiosaurids]]), and is most closely related to [[Titanosauria]], being a close relative of ''[[Euhelopus]]''.<ref name=Ksepka2006/>\n\nDuring the description of ''[[Europatitan]]'' in 2017, a new cladistic analysis was performed. Here, ''Erketu'' was recovered in a [[polytomy]] along ''[[Chubutisaurus]]'' within the Somphospondyli:<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fern\u00e1ndez-Baldor|first1=F. T.|last2=Canudo|first2=J. I.|last3=Huerta|first3=P.|last4=Moreno-Azanza|first4=M.|last5=Montero|first5=D.|date=2017|title=Europatitan eastwoodi, a new sauropod from the lower Cretaceous of Iberia in the initial radiation of somphospondylans in Laurasia|journal=PeerJ|volume=5|pages=e3409|doi=10.7717/peerj.3409|doi-access=free|pmc=5490465|pmid=28674644}}</ref>\n{{clade|style=font-size:100%; line-height:100%;\n|label1=[[Somphospondyli]]\n|1={{clade\n|1=''[[Europatitan|Europatitan eastwoodi]]''\n|2=''[[Tendaguria|Tendaguria tanzaniensis]]''\n|3={{clade\n|1=''[[Sauroposeidon|Sauroposeidon proteles]]\n|2={{clade\n|1=''[[Chubutisaurus|Chubutisaurus insignis]]''\n|2='''''Erketu ellisoni'''''\n|3={{clade\n|1={{clade\n|1={{clade\n|1=[[Titanosauria]]}} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n==Paleoecology==\nThe remains of ''Erketu'' are attributed to the [[Bayan Shireh Formation]],<ref name=Ksepka2010/> which is believed to have been dominated by fluvial and lacrustine enviroments, such as large [[meanders]] and [[lakes]] but also a notorius semi-arid climate.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ishigaki|first1=S.|last2=Tsogtbaatar|first2=K.|last3=Saneyoshi|first3=M.|last4=Mainbayar|first4=B.|last5=Aoki|first5=K.|last6=Ulziitseren|first6=S.|last7=Imayama|first7=T.|last8=Takahashi|first8=A.|last9=Toyoda|first9=S.|last10=Bayardorj|first10=C.|last11=Buyantegsh|first11=B.|last12=Batsukh|first12=J.|last13=Purevsuren|first13=B.|last14=Asai|first14=H.|last15=Tsutanaga|first15=S.|last16=Fujii|first16=K.|date=2016|title=Report of the Okayama University of Science - Mongolian Institute of Paleontology and Geology Joint Expedition in 2016|journal=Bulletin of Research Institute of Natural Sciences|issue=42|pages=33\u221246|url=http://dinosaur.ous.ac.jp/pdf/box/exc2016.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Slowiak|first1=J.|last2=Szczygielski|first2=T.|last3=Ginter|first3=M.|last4=Fostowicz-Frelik|first4=L.|date=2020|title=Uninterrupted growth in a non\u2010polar hadrosaur explains the gigantism among duck\u2010billed dinosaurs|journal=Paleontology|doi=10.1111/pala.12473}}</ref> The age is estimated to be around 102 million and 86 million years ago, [[Cenomanian]] to [[Santonian]] epochs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Danilov|first1=I. G.|last2=Hirayama|first2=R.|last3=Sukhanov|first3=V. B.|last4=Suzuki|first4=S.|last5=Watabe|first5=M.|last6=Vitek|first6=N. S.|title=Cretaceous soft-shelled turtles (Trionychidae) of Mongolia: new diversity, records and a revision|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|date=2014|volume=12|issue=7|doi=10.1080/14772019.2013.847870}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kurumada|first1=Y.|last2=Aoki|first2=S.|last3=Aoki|first3=K.|last4=Kato|first4=D.|last5=Saneyoshi|first5=M.|last6=Tsogtbaatar|first6=K.|last7=Windley|first7=B. F.|last8=Ishigaki|first8=S.|title=Calcite U\u2013Pb age of the Cretaceous vertebrate\u2010bearing Bayn Shire Formation in the Eastern Gobi Desert of Mongolia: usefulness of caliche for age determination|journal=Terra Nova|date=2020|doi=10.1111/ter.12456}}</ref> Here, ''Erketu'' lived alongside diverse dinosaur fauna, such as the predators ''[[Achillobator]]''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Perle|first1=A.|last2=Norell|first2=M. A.|last3=Clark|first3=J.|date=1999|title=A new maniraptoran Theropod\u2212Achillobator giganticus (Dromaeosauridae)\u2212from the Upper Cretaceous of Burkhant, Mongolia|journal=Contributions from the Geology and Mineralogy Chair, National Museum of Mongolia|issue=101|pages=1\u2013105|oclc=69865262}}</ref> and potentially ''[[Alectrosaurus]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Perle|first1=A.|title=O pervoy nakhodke Alektrozavra (Tyrannosauridae, Theropoda) iz pozdnego Mela Mongolii|trans-title=On the first discovery of Alectrosaurus (Tyrannosauridae, Theropoda) in the Late Cretaceous of Mongolia|journal=Shinzhlekh Ukhaany Akademi Geologiin Khureelen|year=1977|volume=3|issue=3|pages=104\u2013113|language=Russian}}</ref> the abundant hadrosauroid ''[[Gobihadros]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tsogtbaatar|first1=K.|last2=Weishampel|first2=D. B.|last3=Evans|first3=D. C.|last4=Watabe|first4=M.|date=2019|title=A new hadrosauroid (Dinosauria: Ornithopoda) from the Late Cretaceous Baynshire Formation of the Gobi Desert (Mongolia)|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=14|issue=4|pages=e0208480|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0208480|doi-access=free|pmid=30995236|pmc=6469754|bibcode=2019PLoSO..1408480T}}</ref> heavy armored ''[[Talarurus]]'' and ''[[Tsagantegia]]'',<ref name=Park2020>{{cite journal|last1=Park|first1=J.|last4=Kobayashi|first4=Y.|last5=Koppelhus|first5=E.|last6=Barsbold|first6=R.|last7=Mateus|first7=O.|last8=Lee|first8=S.|last9=Kim|first9=S. H.|title=Additional skulls of Talarurus plicatospineus (Dinosauria: Ankylosauridae) and implications for paleobiogeography and paleoecology of armored dinosaurs|date=2020|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=108|pages=e104340|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104340}}</ref> and the well-known therizinosaurs ''[[Erlikosaurus]]'' and ''[[Segnosaurus]]''.<ref name=Zanno2016>{{cite journal|last1=Zanno|first1=L. E.|last2=Tsogtbaatar|first2=K.|last3=Chinzorig|first3=T.|last4=Gates|first4=T. A.|title=Specializations of the mandibular anatomy and dentition of Segnosaurus galbinensis (Theropoda: Therizinosauria)|year=2016|journal=PeerJ|volume=4|pages=e1885|doi=10.7717/peerj.1885|doi-access=free|pmid=27069815|pmc=4824891}}</ref> The locality of ''Erketu'' has also yielded an indeterminate/unnamed titanosaur and very abundant fossilized [[fruits]].<ref name=Ksepka2006/><ref name=Ksepka2010/> Some ecological niches were filled by several dinosaurs, such as the [[Browsing (herbivory)|browsers]] ''Erlikosaurus'', ''Segnosaurus''<ref name=Zanno2016/> and Tsagantegia; in contrast, ''Talarurus'' was a [[Grazing (behaviour)|grazer]].<ref name=Park2020/> ''Erketu'' in the other hand, due to its very long neck, was likely a high browser.<ref name=Paul2016/>\n\n[[File:Bayan Shireh Formation Fauna.png|thumb|center|400px|''Erketu'' compared to the known [[Dinosauria]] of the Bayan Shireh Formation (''Erketu'' in brown, next to ''Gobihadros'')]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs|Cretaceous}}\n* [[Mark Norell]]\n* [[Sauropod neck posture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sauropodomorpha|M.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q138872}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2006]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Mongolia]]\n[[Category:Macronarians]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Mark Norell]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erketu"}
{"title_page": "Sue Monk Kidd", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Sue Monk Kidd\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1948|8|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sylvester, Georgia]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = [[Novelist]], [[memoir]]ist\n| period = 1988\u2013present\n| genre = Fiction, Historical Fiction, Memoir\n| subject = \n| notableworks = The Invention of Wings, The Secret Life of Bees, The Mermaid Chair, The Dance of the Dissident Daughter, Traveling with Pomegranates:A Mother-Daughter Story\n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|suemonkkidd.com}}\n}}\n[[File:SMK2020TBOL.jpg|thumb|Sue Monk Kidd]]\n'''Sue Monk Kidd''' (born August 12, 1948) is a writer from Sylvester, Georgia, USA, best known for her novels ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,0_1000034248,00.html?sym=BIO|title=Sue Monk Kidd|publisher=Penguin Group USA|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n85-157706|title=Kidd, Sue Monk|publisher=WorldCat Identities|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> and The Invention of Wings.\n\n== Early life and education==\nKidd was born in [[Sylvester, Georgia]], and attended local schools. She graduated from [[Texas Christian University]] with a [[Bachelor of Science in Nursing|B.S. in nursing]] in 1970. She worked in her twenties as a [[Registered Nurse]] and college [[Nursing educator|nursing instructor]] at the [[Medical College of Georgia]].<ref name=south/>\n\nShe was influenced in her 20s by the writings of [[Thomas Merton]] to explore her inner life.<ref name=nyt/> In her 30s, she took writing courses at [[Emory University]] and Anderson College in South Carolina, now [[Anderson University (South Carolina)|Anderson University]], as well as studying at [[Sewanee Writers' Conference|Sewanee]], [[Bread Loaf Writers' Conference|Bread Loaf]], and other writers' conferences.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the Author |publisher=Sue Monk Kidd| url = http://suemonkkidd.com/author/ | accessdate =April 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe got her start in writing when a personal essay she wrote for a writing class was published in ''[[Guideposts (magazine)|Guideposts]]'' and reprinted in ''[[Reader's Digest]]''. She went on to become a Contributing Editor at ''Guideposts''.\n\nHer first three books were spiritual memoirs describing her experiences in contemplative [[Christianity]], the last telling the story of her journey from traditional Christianity to [[feminist theology]]. ''God's Joyful Surprise: Finding Yourself Loved'' ([[HarperCollins|Harper SanFrancisco]], 1988) is focused on abandoning a hopeless quest for perfection and accepting one is loved as one is. ''When the Heart Waits: Spiritual Direction for Life's Sacred Questions'' (Harper SanFrancisco, 1990) tells of her painful midlife crisis.  Finally, ''The Dance of the Dissident Daughter: A Woman's Journey from Christian Tradition to the Sacred Feminine'' (Harper SanFrancisco, 1996), discussed her encounter with women's spirituality.\n\nHer first novel, ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]'' (2002), is set during the [[American Civil Rights Movement|American civil rights movement of 1964]],<ref name=gua/> telling the story of a white girl who runs away from home to live with a woman who now works as an independent bee-keeper and honey-maker with many of her sisters. It has been adapted as an award-winning play in New York and debuted off Broadway at the Atlantic Theater. The novel was also adapted as a [[The Secret Life of Bees (film)|movie of the same name]] by Fox Searchlight, starring [[Dakota Fanning]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Alicia Keys]] and [[Sophie Okonedo]]. ''The Secret Life of Bees'' movie won two People's Choice Awards at the 35th annual awards ceremony, taking home Best Movie Drama and Best Independent Movie.\n\nHer second novel, ''[[The Mermaid Chair]]'' (2005), won the [[Quill Award#2005 Quill Award winners|2005 Quill Award for General Fiction]]. The story concerns a woman who upon coming home to an island off the coast of South Carolina becomes attracted to a Benedictine monk who is just a few months short of taking his final vows. The title refers to a chair in his monastery carved with mermaids dedicated to a female saint said to be a mermaid before her conversion and who is patroness of the island. \nIt was adapted as a 2006 Lifetime movie [[The Mermaid Chair (film)|of the same name]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |title=Giving Voice, and Finding Her Own: Sue Monk Kidd Tackles Race in 'The Invention of Wings' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/07/books/sue-monk-kidd-tackles-race-in-the-invention-of-wings.html |first=Felicia R. |last=Leejan|newspaper=New York Times |date=January 6, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The movie starred Kim Bassinger and Bruce Greenwood.\n\nIn 2006, ''Firstlight'', a collection of Kidd's early writings, was published in hardcover by Guideposts Books; it was published in paperback by Penguin in 2007.\n\nAfter traveling with her daughter, Ann Kidd Taylor, to sacred sites in Greece, Turkey, and France, Kidd and Taylor co-authored a memoir, ''Traveling with Pomegranates: A Mother-Daughter Story''. Published by Viking in 2009, it appeared on numerous bestseller lists, including the New York Times list and has been published in several languages.\n\nHer 2014 novel, ''The Invention of Wings'', is set during the antebellum years and based on the life of [[Sarah Grimk\u00e9]], a 19th-century [[abolitionism|abolitionist]] and women's rights pioneer.<ref name=gua>{{cite web | title = The Invention of Wings by Sue Monk Kidd \u2013 review | newspaper= The Observer | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/05/invention-wings-monk-kidd-review|date=January 5, 2014|accessdate =April 23, 2014 | first = Anita | last = Sethi  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SUNDAY BOOK REVIEW: Taking Flight: 'The Invention of Wings,' by Sue Monk Kidd|first=Suzanne |last=Bernejan|date= January 24, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/books/review/the-invention-of-wings-by-sue-monk-kidd.html?_r=0 |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The novel debuted at No. 1 on [[New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] and was later selected for [[Oprah's Book Club 2.0]]. In April, Kidd appeared in an interview with Oprah on [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]]'s ''[[Super Soul Sunday]]'' episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/spirit/Oprah-Talks-with-Sue-Monk-Kidd-About-The-Invention-of-Wings|title=Oprah Talks with Sue Monk Kidd About The Invention of Wings|website=oprah.com|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2020 Kidd will publish her much anticipated novel, The Book of Longings.\n\n==Personal life==\nKidd is married to Sanford \"Sandy\" Kidd. The couple have two children, Bob and Ann. She has lived in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[Mt. Pleasant, South Carolina]], Florida, and currently resides in North Carolina.<ref name=south>{{cite web| title = Sue Monk Kidd Profile| publisher = University of South Carolina| url = http://faculty.libsci.sc.edu/literarymap/authors/SMKidd.html| access-date = April 23, 2014| url-status = dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140419015025/http://faculty.libsci.sc.edu/literarymap/authors/SMKidd.html| archive-date = April 19, 2014| df = }}</ref><ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''God's Joyful Surprise: Finding Yourself Loved'', 1988\n* ''When the Heart Waits: Spiritual Direction for Life's Sacred Questions'', 1990\n* ''The Dance of the Dissident Daughter: A Woman's Journey from Christian Tradition to the Sacred Feminine'', 1996\n* ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]'' , 2002\n* ''[[The Mermaid Chair]]'', 2005\n* ''Firstlight: The Early Inspirational Writings of Sue Monk Kidd'', 2006\n* ''Traveling with Pomegranates: A Mother-Daughter Journey to the Sacred Places of Greece, Turkey and France'' (with Ann Kidd Taylor). Viking, 2009\n* ''The Invention of Wings'', 2014\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.suemonkkidd.com Official web site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kidd, Sue Monk}}\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Texas Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sylvester, Georgia]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Nursing educators]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women religious writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:American Quakers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Sue Monk Kidd\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1948|8|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sylvester, Georgia]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = [[Novelist]], [[memoir]]ist\n| period = 1988\u2013present\n| genre = Fiction, Historical Fiction, Memoir\n| subject = \n| notableworks = The Invention of Wings, The Secret Life of Bees, The Mermaid Chair, The Dance of the Dissident Daughter, Traveling with Pomegranates:A Mother-Daughter Story\n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|suemonkkidd.com}}\n}}\n[[File:SMK2020TBOL.jpg|thumb|Sue Monk Kidd]]\n'''Sue Monk Kidd''' (born August 12, 1948) is a writer from Sylvester, Georgia, best known for her novels ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,0_1000034248,00.html?sym=BIO|title=Sue Monk Kidd|publisher=Penguin Group USA|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n85-157706|title=Kidd, Sue Monk|publisher=WorldCat Identities|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> and The Invention of Wings.\n\n== Early life and education==\nKidd was born in [[Sylvester, Georgia]], and attended local schools. She graduated from [[Texas Christian University]] with a [[Bachelor of Science in Nursing|B.S. in nursing]] in 1970. She worked in her twenties as a [[Registered Nurse]] and college [[Nursing educator|nursing instructor]] at the [[Medical College of Georgia]].<ref name=south/>\n\nShe was influenced in her 20s by the writings of [[Thomas Merton]] to explore her inner life.<ref name=nyt/> In her 30s, she took writing courses at [[Emory University]] and Anderson College in South Carolina, now [[Anderson University (South Carolina)|Anderson University]], as well as studying at [[Sewanee Writers' Conference|Sewanee]], [[Bread Loaf Writers' Conference|Bread Loaf]], and other writers' conferences.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the Author |publisher=Sue Monk Kidd| url = http://suemonkkidd.com/author/ | accessdate =April 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe got her start in writing when a personal essay she wrote for a writing class was published in ''[[Guideposts (magazine)|Guideposts]]'' and reprinted in ''[[Reader's Digest]]''. She went on to become a Contributing Editor at ''Guideposts''.\n\nHer first three books were spiritual memoirs describing her experiences in contemplative [[Christianity]], the last telling the story of her journey from traditional Christianity to [[feminist theology]]. ''God's Joyful Surprise: Finding Yourself Loved'' ([[HarperCollins|Harper SanFrancisco]], 1988) is focused on abandoning a hopeless quest for perfection and accepting one is loved as one is. ''When the Heart Waits: Spiritual Direction for Life's Sacred Questions'' (Harper SanFrancisco, 1990) tells of her painful midlife crisis.  Finally, ''The Dance of the Dissident Daughter: A Woman's Journey from Christian Tradition to the Sacred Feminine'' (Harper SanFrancisco, 1996), discussed her encounter with women's spirituality.\n\nHer first novel, ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]'' (2002), is set during the [[American Civil Rights Movement|American civil rights movement of 1964]],<ref name=gua/> telling the story of a white girl who runs away from home to live with a woman who now works as an independent bee-keeper and honey-maker with many of her sisters. It has been adapted as an award-winning play in New York and debuted off Broadway at the Atlantic Theater. The novel was also adapted as a [[The Secret Life of Bees (film)|movie of the same name]] by Fox Searchlight, starring [[Dakota Fanning]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Alicia Keys]] and [[Sophie Okonedo]]. ''The Secret Life of Bees'' movie won two People's Choice Awards at the 35th annual awards ceremony, taking home Best Movie Drama and Best Independent Movie.\n\nHer second novel, ''[[The Mermaid Chair]]'' (2005), won the [[Quill Award#2005 Quill Award winners|2005 Quill Award for General Fiction]]. The story concerns a woman who upon coming home to an island off the coast of South Carolina becomes attracted to a Benedictine monk who is just a few months short of taking his final vows. The title refers to a chair in his monastery carved with mermaids dedicated to a female saint said to be a mermaid before her conversion and who is patroness of the island. \nIt was adapted as a 2006 Lifetime movie [[The Mermaid Chair (film)|of the same name]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |title=Giving Voice, and Finding Her Own: Sue Monk Kidd Tackles Race in 'The Invention of Wings' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/07/books/sue-monk-kidd-tackles-race-in-the-invention-of-wings.html |first=Felicia R. |last=Leejan|newspaper=New York Times |date=January 6, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The movie starred Kim Bassinger and Bruce Greenwood.\n\nIn 2006, ''Firstlight'', a collection of Kidd's early writings, was published in hardcover by Guideposts Books; it was published in paperback by Penguin in 2007.\n\nAfter traveling with her daughter, Ann Kidd Taylor, to sacred sites in Greece, Turkey, and France, Kidd and Taylor co-authored a memoir, ''Traveling with Pomegranates: A Mother-Daughter Story''. Published by Viking in 2009, it appeared on numerous bestseller lists, including the New York Times list and has been published in several languages.\n\nHer 2014 novel, ''The Invention of Wings'', is set during the antebellum years and based on the life of [[Sarah Grimk\u00e9]], a 19th-century [[abolitionism|abolitionist]] and women's rights pioneer.<ref name=gua>{{cite web | title = The Invention of Wings by Sue Monk Kidd \u2013 review | newspaper= The Observer | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/05/invention-wings-monk-kidd-review|date=January 5, 2014|accessdate =April 23, 2014 | first = Anita | last = Sethi  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SUNDAY BOOK REVIEW: Taking Flight: 'The Invention of Wings,' by Sue Monk Kidd|first=Suzanne |last=Bernejan|date= January 24, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/books/review/the-invention-of-wings-by-sue-monk-kidd.html?_r=0 |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The novel debuted at No. 1 on [[New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] and was later selected for [[Oprah's Book Club 2.0]]. In April, Kidd appeared in an interview with Oprah on [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|OWN]]'s ''[[Super Soul Sunday]]'' episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/spirit/Oprah-Talks-with-Sue-Monk-Kidd-About-The-Invention-of-Wings|title=Oprah Talks with Sue Monk Kidd About The Invention of Wings|website=oprah.com|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2020 Kidd will publish her much anticipated novel, The Book of Longings.\n\n==Personal life==\nKidd is married to Sanford \"Sandy\" Kidd. The couple have two children, Bob and Ann. She has lived in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[Mt. Pleasant, South Carolina]], Florida, and currently resides in North Carolina.<ref name=south>{{cite web| title = Sue Monk Kidd Profile| publisher = University of South Carolina| url = http://faculty.libsci.sc.edu/literarymap/authors/SMKidd.html| access-date = April 23, 2014| url-status = dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140419015025/http://faculty.libsci.sc.edu/literarymap/authors/SMKidd.html| archive-date = April 19, 2014| df = }}</ref><ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''God's Joyful Surprise: Finding Yourself Loved'', 1988\n* ''When the Heart Waits: Spiritual Direction for Life's Sacred Questions'', 1990\n* ''The Dance of the Dissident Daughter: A Woman's Journey from Christian Tradition to the Sacred Feminine'', 1996\n* ''[[The Secret Life of Bees (novel)|The Secret Life of Bees]]'' , 2002\n* ''[[The Mermaid Chair]]'', 2005\n* ''Firstlight: The Early Inspirational Writings of Sue Monk Kidd'', 2006\n* ''Traveling with Pomegranates: A Mother-Daughter Journey to the Sacred Places of Greece, Turkey and France'' (with Ann Kidd Taylor). Viking, 2009\n* ''The Invention of Wings'', 2014\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.suemonkkidd.com Official web site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kidd, Sue Monk}}\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Texas Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n